WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.800
Thanks very much, and thank you to you all for not scheduling your flights out too early.

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:15.800
My name is Ian Fellows.

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:17.400
I'm the CEO of Fellow Statistics.

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:22.700
We're a small boutique data science and statistics consultancy in San Diego.

00:00:22.700 --> 00:00:30.660
Today I'm going to be talking to you about a package that I developed called IPC that

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:38.180
was really born out of some problems and frustrations we were having dealing with Shiny apps when

00:00:38.180 --> 00:00:44.299
there are long running processes involved or computationally intensive.

00:00:44.299 --> 00:00:45.580
Now this is R, right?

00:00:45.580 --> 00:00:50.580
This is a statistical computing language, so we shouldn't be too surprised when things

00:00:50.580 --> 00:00:58.220
take a significant amount of time doing bootstraps, Markov chain Monte Carlo, or various complicated

00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:00.779
analytic techniques.

00:01:00.779 --> 00:01:04.739
And there are some design considerations that you need to think about when you're dealing

00:01:04.739 --> 00:01:10.339
with long running computationally intensive tasks, and you want to make those available

00:01:10.339 --> 00:01:14.660
to a wider audience through a Shiny application.

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:20.519
The first and arguably most important thing is don't block everything, right?

00:01:20.519 --> 00:01:26.160
So if one user is doing something computationally complex, it shouldn't block the entire server

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:32.320
from being able to do any computation, so another user's user interface all of a sudden

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:36.080
locks up and they have no idea why.

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:42.279
The second is that a single user, so if you've got multiple things going on in your application

00:01:42.279 --> 00:01:47.320
and one of them is a computationally complex task, well, all of the other interface elements

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:52.599
and outputs should not be blocked and hang while the code is executing.

00:01:52.599 --> 00:01:56.199
That leads to a poor user experience.

00:01:56.199 --> 00:02:00.720
And third, the user needs to have insight into that computation.

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:04.680
You know, if a user doesn't know whether a computation is going to take ten seconds or

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:11.960
ten hours, it's, you know, it's incredibly frustrating, and because all of the speakers

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:16.919
are contractually obligated to put a meme up, you know, this is kind of how I feel.

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:18.520
It's very uncomfortable.

00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:21.759
My favorite movie, Hocus Pocus.

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:30.160
It's very uncomfortable, and, you know, it's not something that's great for your design.

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:34.240
Okay, so let's say that you've got a long-running task.

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:37.520
This is sort of the hello world of long-running tasks.

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:46.259
You've got your text input, which is who are we going to say hello to today, an action

00:02:46.259 --> 00:02:51.020
button that when we click it will run the thing, and then in the text output, we're

00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:56.339
going to put hello to whoever we want.

00:02:56.339 --> 00:03:01.740
So we've got a reactive value, and that value is being rendered into the result, and then

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:06.300
when we hit run, we've got a nice little progress bar here, which is going to close, and then

00:03:06.300 --> 00:03:08.940
we're doing our long-running task down here.

00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:16.059
We're updating our progress bar, and in the end, we put our salutation in there, right?

00:03:16.059 --> 00:03:24.699
So very simple, and it's sort of like how you would go about it at, you know, just going

00:03:24.699 --> 00:03:28.940
ahead and naively writing your code.

00:03:28.940 --> 00:03:33.059
So I'm going to go ahead and run this.

00:03:33.059 --> 00:03:34.059
Hello world.

00:03:34.059 --> 00:03:37.259
You know, I don't care about the world.

00:03:37.259 --> 00:03:44.580
I only care about you guys, so we want to say hello to you guys.

00:03:44.580 --> 00:03:47.139
So we've got a nice little progress bar here.

00:03:47.139 --> 00:03:50.259
I understand how long it's going to take.

00:03:50.259 --> 00:04:06.740
Of course, there are some major issues with doing it this sort of naive way, and the good

00:04:06.740 --> 00:04:08.179
thing is the user's shown progress.

00:04:08.179 --> 00:04:10.059
I get insight into the computation.

00:04:10.059 --> 00:04:14.100
The bad thing is the entire server's blocked.

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:19.859
We can do anything else while we're figuring out how to say hello to whoever we want to

00:04:19.859 --> 00:04:24.700
say hello to, and no other output values in the user interface, if there were multiple

00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:30.380
output things, would be updated while this computation is running.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:33.140
Also not on here, the user can't cancel that operation.

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:37.579
If they decide, oh, these parameters, I don't want to do 100,000 bootstraps because that's

00:04:37.579 --> 00:04:38.579
going to take 10 years.

00:04:38.579 --> 00:04:41.299
I want to lower it to 100.

00:04:41.299 --> 00:04:46.260
There's no way to cancel that operation.

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:55.500
The solution which Joe presented at the last RStudio conference is to utilize asynchronous

00:04:55.500 --> 00:05:01.980
computation, to kick that long-running task out to a separate process and then return

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:03.640
the values back.

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:07.619
So here's an implementation of hello world with async.

00:05:07.619 --> 00:05:11.739
Basically everything's the same except for now we're kicking out using the future package,

00:05:11.739 --> 00:05:16.019
our long-running computation is happening outside.

00:05:16.019 --> 00:05:23.820
And then we get the result of that computation, and then it kicks back to our local and assigns

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:26.660
that to our reactive value.

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:27.660
Okay.

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:28.660
So this is good.

00:05:28.660 --> 00:05:34.140
You'll notice that we assign to a temporary value here the value of our input, and we

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:43.619
have to do that because the process that you kick off as a child can have no interaction,

00:05:43.619 --> 00:05:45.859
doesn't have access to the reactive context.

00:05:45.859 --> 00:05:50.299
It's an entirely separate process, and these two can't talk to each other.

00:05:50.299 --> 00:05:58.980
And so you need to assign that to a temporary value which is then shipped off to that process

00:05:58.980 --> 00:06:01.420
for utilization.

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:04.820
Okay.

00:06:04.820 --> 00:06:09.179
So then we can go ahead and just run that.

00:06:09.179 --> 00:06:19.619
So with async, now we hit run.

00:06:19.619 --> 00:06:21.100
Oh, God, how long is this going to take?

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:26.899
I don't know, because we don't have a progress bar anymore, and the reason why we don't have

00:06:26.899 --> 00:06:31.019
a progress bar is because we don't have access to our reactive context.

00:06:31.019 --> 00:06:34.399
There's no communication that can happen.

00:06:34.399 --> 00:06:42.660
And so we finally get our hello world back, but we've had to drop that progress bar.

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:46.940
Okay.

00:06:46.940 --> 00:06:52.500
So the good thing is the server's not blocked, and actually the way that we coded it up,

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:55.619
output values can be updated while that computation is running.

00:06:55.619 --> 00:06:59.739
The bad is we've lost all visibility into the computation.

00:06:59.739 --> 00:07:00.859
It doesn't know about the server.

00:07:00.859 --> 00:07:02.380
The server doesn't know about it.

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:09.540
The only time they can interact is after the computation is done.

00:07:09.540 --> 00:07:12.820
So that's where the IPC package comes along.

00:07:12.820 --> 00:07:23.140
IPC is a package that's devoted to providing mechanism to communicate back and forth between

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:33.339
processes and to ship computations and expressions between these threads for execution.

00:07:33.339 --> 00:07:37.019
Now here's just a simple code.

00:07:37.019 --> 00:07:38.339
Here we create a queue.

00:07:38.339 --> 00:07:43.019
Now these messaging queues can be backed by some sort of external database that both of

00:07:43.019 --> 00:07:44.980
the processes have access to.

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:53.019
By default that is done via temporary files using the TXT queue package.

00:07:53.019 --> 00:07:54.579
But other backings are available.

00:07:54.579 --> 00:07:59.459
For instance, Redis is also an implemented option.

00:07:59.459 --> 00:08:05.899
Now each queue has a consumer that contains methods for processing things from the queue

00:08:05.899 --> 00:08:09.220
and a producer to fire off messages to the queue.

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:10.540
So here we have a future.

00:08:10.540 --> 00:08:11.540
We're going to create a future.

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:18.920
It's going to just basically run forever, periodically having the consumer run consume.

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:24.959
And then in our main thread we're going to sell the producer to fire off a message to

00:08:24.959 --> 00:08:32.880
evaluate the expression stop that child in the future.

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:39.440
So when that consume is called and it reads the message, it will process it and execute

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:43.840
the expression stop that child.

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:51.159
And then the future will throw an error and the future will stop.

00:08:51.159 --> 00:08:53.119
So important methods.

00:08:53.119 --> 00:08:55.000
On the consumer side you've got consume.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:02.000
This will process all of the messages on the queues and it will evaluate those messages

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.119
in the environment which you provide it.

00:09:05.119 --> 00:09:08.080
By default that's the environment in which it was called.

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:18.320
It's similar except it just runs consume periodically as long as R is idle.

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:26.840
Also we have the queue comes shipped with the ability to handle a couple of different

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:34.020
types of messages, but you can also add your own custom handlers to handle particular signals

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:36.280
and messages that you want to send.

00:09:36.280 --> 00:09:41.320
On the producer side you fire off signals using the fired method and there's a couple

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:44.760
of special ones that are useful.

00:09:44.760 --> 00:09:54.159
You can fire eval will signal to evaluate an expression, fire call will signal to call

00:09:54.159 --> 00:09:59.840
a function with arguments dot, dot, dot, or fire do call will fire the function called

00:09:59.840 --> 00:10:04.020
name with parameters list param.

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:10.299
So basically you can have your own custom handlers, but because evaluation and calls

00:10:10.299 --> 00:10:14.380
are so flexible, you can basically do any sort of computational message that you want

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:21.020
to send via fire call, fire eval or fire call.

00:10:21.020 --> 00:10:22.539
So here's an example.

00:10:22.539 --> 00:10:26.820
Before we saw sending a message from the parent to the future.

00:10:26.820 --> 00:10:29.780
Here we're going to send from the future to the child.

00:10:29.780 --> 00:10:36.260
So we create a queue and then in the future we're going to fire an eval, which is going

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:38.739
to print index.

00:10:38.739 --> 00:10:44.820
And then what we're going to do is over here, so when you fire eval, it will substitute

00:10:44.820 --> 00:10:48.260
the values in the second argument into the expression.

00:10:48.260 --> 00:10:54.940
So we're going to substitute I in for index here and so I is going from 1 to 100.

00:10:54.940 --> 00:11:00.460
So this will basically count from 1 to 100 and it will say, hey, go print this out and

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:07.820
here in the parent thread.

00:11:07.820 --> 00:11:16.859
And so that's pretty easy.

00:11:16.859 --> 00:11:19.580
So you can just run that.

00:11:19.580 --> 00:11:26.260
And so basically while R is idle in the thread, it will just keep on printing out these numbers

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:33.460
until it gets to 100 and that's all coming from the other process.

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:37.799
Okay.

00:11:37.799 --> 00:11:42.780
So finally we're getting back to Shiny.

00:11:42.780 --> 00:11:46.780
We've got some special stuff in this package specifically for Shiny because that's really

00:11:46.780 --> 00:11:49.739
the major use case that we're trying to target.

00:11:49.739 --> 00:11:54.179
Shiny queue creates a queue with a few extras specifically for Shiny applications.

00:11:54.179 --> 00:11:59.940
It also does cleanup of the queue and temporary files and everything on session end so you

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:02.979
don't have to worry about any of that stuff.

00:12:02.979 --> 00:12:07.760
It's also got a couple of methods, fire notify and fire assign reactive for creating notifications

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:14.140
or assigning values to reactive values specifically.

00:12:14.140 --> 00:12:18.380
And also we've got two really important classes.

00:12:18.380 --> 00:12:25.580
Async progress is a drop-in replacement for Shiny's progress class that will allow you

00:12:25.580 --> 00:12:32.900
to do progress bars in your long-running task.

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:35.500
Async interrupter is another one that's important.

00:12:35.500 --> 00:12:38.219
It's a class for sending interrupt signals.

00:12:38.219 --> 00:12:43.299
So you just call the interrupt method in, let's say, your Shiny application and then

00:12:43.299 --> 00:12:49.059
periodically within the future you call exec interrupts and it will check for any interrupts

00:12:49.059 --> 00:12:53.659
that have been signaled and will throw an error.

00:12:53.659 --> 00:13:07.020
So we can take a look at two of those in practice in our example application.

00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:09.500
So here's a very similar application.

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:14.419
So we've just got a run and a cancel button and some output.

00:13:14.419 --> 00:13:21.619
So here we're creating a new interrupter and then when we hit the run button we're going

00:13:21.619 --> 00:13:30.820
to create a new progress bar and now we've kicked off into our future and the progress,

00:13:30.820 --> 00:13:36.500
we're going to increment the progress within our future and we're going to check for any

00:13:36.500 --> 00:13:42.260
interrupts and we'll throw an error if we hit one.

00:13:42.260 --> 00:13:48.900
And then over here, if the cancel buttons hit, then we signal an interrupt.

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:52.979
And so, yeah, we can see this working, so we're doing a complex analysis, hey, this

00:13:52.979 --> 00:13:59.619
is great, I understand how long this is going to take, I get out a very insightful result,

00:13:59.619 --> 00:14:02.380
which is fantastic.

00:14:02.380 --> 00:14:08.940
And this is cancelable, so I can use or interrupt it and basically this gives you the ability

00:14:08.940 --> 00:14:14.820
to have a bunch of different parameters, the user can try it, they can say, oh, no, I should

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:19.979
have done 1,000 bootstraps, not 10,000, I can customize it so it will take a reasonable

00:14:19.979 --> 00:14:23.539
amount of time according to my own definition.

00:14:23.539 --> 00:14:31.020
How much time do I have left?

00:14:31.020 --> 00:14:32.020
Five and a half minutes.

00:14:32.659 --> 00:14:35.940
So I can show you another one that's kind of fun.

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:45.340
So we're all familiar with the old faithful geyser example that Shiny has.

00:14:45.340 --> 00:14:51.900
And it's just a simple application that allows you to create a histogram and change the number

00:14:51.900 --> 00:14:53.179
of bins.

00:14:53.179 --> 00:14:58.299
Now what I've added to this is a little bit of kaleidoscope action.

00:14:58.299 --> 00:15:03.659
So when we change it, we're going to kick off a future.

00:15:03.659 --> 00:15:10.380
Well, first of all, we create a new Shiny queue and we start execution of the consumer.

00:15:10.380 --> 00:15:16.700
And we have a color variable that we're going to change in that future.

00:15:16.700 --> 00:15:20.500
And here we're going to cycle through the rainbow.

00:15:20.619 --> 00:15:31.460
So every second, we're going to change the color of our histogram to a different color.

00:15:31.460 --> 00:15:43.580
And this is going to happen regardless of us changing around the actual slider value.

00:15:43.580 --> 00:15:46.219
So if you don't remember what it looks like, it looks like this.

00:15:46.219 --> 00:15:48.020
It's a nice little thing.

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:50.219
So we're cycling through.

00:15:50.940 --> 00:15:58.219
But while we're cycling through, while we're doing something, we can change this slider

00:15:58.219 --> 00:16:01.539
here and it will keep cycling through.

00:16:01.539 --> 00:16:07.659
So I know this is a bit of a toy, but it shows you that you can start to make your Shiny

00:16:07.659 --> 00:16:13.260
apps do multiple things at the same time and have multiple different interactive components

00:16:13.260 --> 00:16:18.140
that are all dynamically occurring together.

00:16:18.140 --> 00:16:23.500
And that's what the power of that sort of communication framework, the ability to ship

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:30.979
executions between the different processes that you have running, allows you to do.

00:16:30.979 --> 00:16:32.580
So that is all I have.

00:16:32.580 --> 00:16:35.500
I'm interested in any questions.

00:16:36.059 --> 00:16:38.700
Thank you.

00:16:38.700 --> 00:16:51.059
And a question about the, like the producer and consumers.

00:16:51.059 --> 00:16:54.020
Is it like bidirectional, as they both are producers and consumers?

00:16:54.020 --> 00:16:57.739
Or does communication flow in one direction?

00:16:57.739 --> 00:16:59.039
Yeah.

00:16:59.039 --> 00:17:05.640
So anyone can call it, so you could, the object, the queue object is sort of like a wrapper.

00:17:05.640 --> 00:17:09.400
It contains both a consumer and a producer object.

00:17:09.400 --> 00:17:22.359
So you can call any of the consumers, you can call any of the producer, producer methods.

00:17:22.359 --> 00:17:26.719
Have you seen how this scales by number of users, and what's the overhead on calling

00:17:26.719 --> 00:17:31.520
the, reading the queuing function?

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:38.000
So the overhead is writing and reading the message to file.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:43.199
So that's pretty quick.

00:17:43.199 --> 00:17:48.959
There was a little bit of an overhead, but we fixed that issue when there were very large

00:17:48.959 --> 00:17:49.959
messages.

00:17:49.959 --> 00:17:55.040
But especially if you're doing smaller messages, the overhead is very minimal.

00:17:55.040 --> 00:18:00.280
And you can also change the backing to a different, faster connection if you wanted

00:18:00.280 --> 00:18:00.439
to.

